This solution works if the WEB-INF folder is unpacked during deploy. And also works when the data folder remains in the war archive.

Your swap method doesn&#39;t return anything. So `head` is not updated. You can make it return value of the method like:

    public static Node swap(Node head, Node current, Node next, Node prev){
       if(current == head){
            current.next = next.next;
            next.next = current;
            return next;
        }
        else{
            prev.next = current.next;
            current.next = next.next;
            next.next = current;
            return head;
        }
    }

and then in method `bubbleSort()` assign it to head like:

    head = swap(head,current,next,prev);

Your code sorts the list correctly, but when the local `head` variable gets assigned a different node reference, this does not alter the *caller&#39;s* `head` variable.

You can solve this in at least two ways:

1. Have `bubbleSort` *return* the `head` of the sorted list, so the caller can assign it to their own `head` variable

2. Create a `LinkedList` class that has a `head` member, and defined the `bubbleSort` method on that class: it can then alter that `head` member.

The first idea needs these changes:

```
    public static Node bubbleSort(Node head){
        if(head == null){
            System.out.println(&quot;List is empty&quot;);
            return head; // &lt;--
        }
        else if(head.next == null){
            System.out.println(&quot;only one element in LL&quot;);
            return head; // &lt;--
        }
        else {
            // ...unchanged code...
        }
        return head; // &lt;-- return the head of the sorted list
     }
```

